you should be able to use $lookup. $lookup is used to look up a document in another collection, it works more like a join. An example would be as below.

    db.users.aggregate([{
      $lookup: {
         from: &quot;countries&quot;,
         localField: &quot;country&quot;,
         foreignField: &quot;_id&quot;,
         as: &quot;cname&quot;
      }
    }])

in the above query you are matching records from user collection against countries collection on field country = _id.

you can then introduce a pipeline agreegator inside the lookup to apply the filter. An example for your reference that i picked from the mongodb documentation

    db.orders.aggregate([
       {
          $lookup:
             {
               from: &quot;warehouses&quot;,
               let: { order_item: &quot;$item&quot;, order_qty: &quot;$ordered&quot; },
               pipeline: [
                  { $match:
                     { $expr:
                        { $and:
                           [
                             { $eq: [ &quot;$stock_item&quot;,  &quot;$$order_item&quot; ] },
                             { $gte: [ &quot;$instock&quot;, &quot;$$order_qty&quot; ] }
                           ]
                        }
                     }
                  },
                  { $project: { stock_item: 0, _id: 0 } }
               ],
               as: &quot;stockdata&quot;
             }
        }
    ])

you can find quite a good explanation and samples here on the official [MongoDB document for lookup][1] 


  [1]: https://docs.mongodb.com/manual/reference/operator/aggregation/lookup/

